Analysis on Methods of Predicting Energy Consumption¶

Fall 2019

Natalie Fedorova - Performed spatial predictive modeling on census tract level, and model validation with Howard et al.

Owen McGrattan - Performed temporal predictive modeling on building level.

Abstract (5 points)¶

The research domain in predicting electricity consumption is already quite broad, using both high-level methodologies and robust-system modeling. Because both city governments and their residents hold stock in ensuring that energy is being used efficiently, the reality of climate change poses a challenge for cities to reduce their $CO_2$ pollution by examining how energy efficient their buildings are. If areas vulnerable to energy losses can be identified, then resources like retrofitting measures or installation of distributed generation can be delivered, boosting a resilient energy landscape. Addressing this need, we chose Chicago, IL as our core city to model, and we also separated our analysis into a spatial component and a temporal component in order to see which approach yielded stronger results. In the spatial analysis, we broke down our observations into census tract groupings and used a combination of building characteristics and median household income as our feature space. In our temporal component, we first generated some models to look at predicting a yearly consumption total in kWh, and then transitioned to generating separate models for each month within a year in order to see if there are consistencies in model strength across months. Because of the heavy skew in the density distribution of energy use intensity, no model constructed was ever strong across training, testing and cross-validation, so instead a healthy balance was maintained, resulting in average household age and median income being top-performing predictors. While predicting on a yearly total generated a strong model, this strength was very noisy when individual models were built on months, suggesting that there are some additional features that could help us elucidate consumption behavior on the building or census tract level, which ultimately points to a data issue.

Project Background (5 points)¶

Predicting electricity and energy consumption across various scopes of space and time has been a long-time topic of interest amongst researchers and stakeholders in the energy market. In the wake of climate change, establishing energy efficient building design and promoting smart electricity use are two major ways cities can mitigate their contributions to global $CO_2$ emissions. If cities can identify the areas where consumption per square meter, or energy end use intensity, is relatively higher, then they can allocate aid in the form of retrofitting or even look towards establishing strategic deployment of distributed energy generation, such as at-home or commercial rooftop solar panels. Moreover, metrics of consumption can help to complete the picture of a city's welfare if correlation can be established between consumption rates and other known parameters of welfare assessment.

High-level research has already been conducted on predicting consumption. For example, Jones et al. explores modeling UC Berkeley's Sutardja Dai Hall, using several modeling approaches to predict within a small window of time, and still could not get a highly performing model because it had to capture the hourly variation in consumption while also responding strongly to the chosen predictors. This is the core issue with mapping consumption: it is difficult to fine-tune prediction in the abstract sense without making many separate models specific to one area, or one time period. Beyond that, from the perspective of applying these models in real life and broadly sourcing relevant data, there is a tension between trying to build single-parameter models, like in the study conducted in Howard et al. where just square footage was used to predict energy use (delivering a coefficient of energy use intensity), and using many parameters that may be more difficult to obtain data for, resulting in models with limited sharing potential. Despite using readily-available U.S. city data, it was difficult to find comprehensive building data that had robust granularity and was recent. Given this, we turn to broad building data from Allegheny County, New York state, and the city of Chicago to try and gather a sense of electrical consumption variations over a multi-year timespan within a building type. It must be noted that our conclusions in this space are also limited due to the lack of information on infrastructural changes that would affect consumption, such as the introduction and installation of LED lighting en masse to much of the nation.

Ultimately, the approach to predicting electricity consumption is highly dependent on the immediate applications of the model, and it is almost impossible to build a one-size-fits-all model even within one scope, such as space or time. From this, we decided to focus our work on the city of Chicago and try a few different layers of analysis in hopes of using many general building features to predict on a spatial scale, and also on a temporal scale. One part of the analysis is a spatial regression on the census tract level, where the aim is to predict the total energy intensity for each census tract in Chicago in 2010. The parameters used to frame this prediction include building characteristic totals broken down into building subtypes, as well as median household income for a given tract. Another part of our regression analysis is exploring total energy consumption on the individual building level for both yearly and monthly timescales. The aim is to draw out identifiable characteristics of electricity consumption outside of square footage and discern where the variance in electrical consumption may lie.

Project Objective (5 points)¶

The central objective of this project is to analyze which methods of predicting energy consumption work best on a citywide scale like Chicago, IL, and whether we can extract more accuracy using an approach that predicts over some time period, or over spatial increments. Determining consumption on some scale is relevant to the reality of climate change in that increasing the energy efficiency of buildings can help to reduce city-wide emissions, to assess the need to integrate demand-response measures, and to allocate distributed generation resources. Moreover, bringing in a parameter like household income and measuring its significance in energy modeling can help us ascertain if energy use intensity can serve as an indicator of welfare. Lastly, we aim to expand on the existing domain by predicting a coefficient of energy end-use intensity given square footage while predicting energy use, parallel to the study done in Howard et. al, and seeing how the prediction performs alongside measured energy intensity.

1. Data Origins¶

Chicago Energy Usage 2010 is sourced from the Chicago Data Portal, and was accessible directly from the site via a downloadable .csv file. The set itself was found using a Google search.

Income by Location was taken from "datausa", and was found using a Google search that led to an interactive map whose tabulated data source was available for download in .csv format.

New York State Government Building Energy Use Intensity Data: Beginning State Fiscal Year 2010 is sourced from the New York State Government data access portal, and the .csv file was directly downloadable from a data interaction API labeled with the set name. The set was discovered using Google.

Allegheny County Municipal Building Energy Usage was retrieved from data.gov, a governmental database, and the .xlsx file was obtainable from the dataset webpage through a download link. This set was found using Google search.

Lastly, Chicago Energy Benchmarking was also taken from the Chicago Data Portal, with the same data accessibility features, and was discovered through Google search.

2. Structure, Granularity, Scope, Temporality, Faithfulness (SGSTF)¶

Chicago Energy Usage 2010

  • Structure: This dataset is in .csv format, where each row represents a single recorded building in 2010 Chicago. The corresponding columns include information on monthly electricity and natural gas energy usage (kWh, therms) as well as building characteristics that describe physical components and occupancy metrics. In addition, each building is categorized by both the census block and community that it belongs to. Since we have columns for each month and for the annual total electricity/energy consumption, the data overall is not nested. All columns are imported as string data types.
  • Granularity: Each record is a building in Chicago, whose characteristics are assumed to be constant for the year 2010. Within each row, we have 12 columns for both electricity and energy consumption which represent the monthly totals, so we can potentially expand this dataset to have monthly precision. The dataset includes summary statistics such as annual consumption average and standard deviation, but we do not use these columns in our analysis. Instead, the metrics we use are monthly and yearly totals. For one part of our analysis, we aggregate to the census tract level in order to have a sense of broader spatial diversity in consumption.
  • Scope: "The electricity data comprises 68 percent of overall electrical usage in the city while gas data comprises 81 percent of all gas consumption in Chicago for 2010" according to the Chicago Data Portal, so we observe the majority of the overall consumption in the city. There are some null values amongst all columns, which reduces this number by some percent, but overall we sample more than half of the behavior of the city.
  • Temporality: Time is distinguished on a monthly level in this dataset as individual columns for which we have consumption totals.
  • Faithfulness: As mentioned, there is a notable about of null values that are filtered out of the dataset, but overall there is not much data value cleaning that needs to be done that suggests that the data is falsified or badly constructed.

Income by Location

  • Structure: This dataset is in .csv format, where where each row represents a distinct census tract within 2013-2017 Cook County, IL. The columns contain information about the location of the census tract, its identification number, and the median household income as well as an associated margin of error for each tract. There is an additional column that tells us that we are not breaking the income information down by race, instead looking at the total population.
  • Granularity: Each record is a census tract in Cook County at a specified year between 2013-2017, and the income at this level for each year is summarized using the median value. We will later be matching each 2013 median income value with the corresponding census tracts in the Chicago Energy Usage 2010 dataset, though we recognize the obvious mismatch between the sampled years. This is due to lack of accessible energy and income data that either is more recent or farther in the past, respectively.
  • Scope: This dataset encompasses 2013 to 2017, and looks at Cook County census tracts, which is broader than the scope of our analysis, so we will use a subset (in time and space) of this set for our modeling needs.
  • Temporality: Time is captured on a yearly basis over the span of five years, and is represented as a series of individual observations in each tract for a given year. There are no null values to remove for yearly data.
  • Faithfulness: The dataset is very clean. It has an additional component that classifies the racial composition of each observation that is, for our purposes, not needed, but this is probably because the dataset was generated as part of a larger set, and does not represent any shortcoming of the data.

New York State Government Building Energy Use Intensity Data: Beginning State Fiscal Year 2010

  • Structure: This is a csv formatted file where each row represents a given state building in a given year. The columns contain general information like address, zip code, floor area, and source kBtu.
  • Granularity: Each record is for a different municipal building in New York state for different years.
  • Scope: The dataset covers some 300 or so buildings in New York state with dates ranging from 2010 to 2017.
  • Temporality: Each of the date periods is represented as a two year interval (i.e. 2010-11). I would normally be concerned about this but for the purposes of measuring variance across buildings we are only looking within our own set so it is okay.
  • Faithfulness: There is not a lot of data outside of electricity consumption to be explored here but the dataset itself is very clean.

Allegheny County Municipal Building Energy Usage

  • Structure: This is a csv formatted file where each row represents a given building for a given year much like the previous dataset. The columns contain information largely on building energy consumption which we are largely not concerned with.
  • Granularity: Each record is for a municipal building in Allegheny County for different years.
  • Scope: The data set covers a few hundred buildings from 2009-2014.
  • Temporality: Each date period represents consumption over that year. This date formatting is in line with everything else in the project and is easier for interpretability than the dataset above.
  • Faithfulness: Again we have a clean dataset but there are a lot of column values that are of little value to us. We’re really only looking for electricity consumption here.

Chicago Energy Benchmarking

  • Structure: This is a csv file similar in format to our main Chicago electricity consumption dataset. We have information on general location info building type and gross area along with many other types of energy consumption.
  • Granularity: Like the other two datasets mentioned directly above, each row represents a building for a given year.
  • Scope: This set represents some ~200 non-residential buildings in Chicago from 2014-2017.
  • Temporality: Each row represents totals over the given year listed in the Year column.
  • Faithfulness: We don’t have much need for most of the data in the set, once again we want the electricity consumption.

Just looking through the data we have a good amount of missing electrical data. However we ought to be careful in how we separate as often where there is missing electrical data there is thermal data and vicea versa. We should split into at least two different sets.

Also for the purposes of this set we want to remove columns that we will not use for prediction of our total electricity output response variable. Off the bat this includes the monthly totals for kwh and therm (if they even exist for rows in the electric set). In all we are most interested with the columns at the beginning and end of the set. It'll be better to pick these all out by hand.

# Establish parameters of interest, as well as each building type

census_tracts = chicago_2010["CENSUS TRACT"].unique() # 803 Census Tracts
features = ["TOTAL UNITS", "AVERAGE STORIES","AVERAGE BUILDING AGE",
            "AVERAGE HOUSESIZE","OCCUPIED UNITS","RENTER-OCCUPIED HOUSING UNITS",
            "OCCUPIED HOUSING UNITS"]
building_types = ["RDTL 7+", "RDTL <7", "COMM 7+", "COMM <7"]

# Convert the consumption columns to numbers and remove comma separators
chicago_quant_vars = chicago_2010[np.append(features,["TOTAL KWH", "KWH TOTAL SQFT"]) ].replace(to_replace =',', value = '', regex = True).astype(float)

# Concatenate both our features and components of the desired response variable into one dataframe
# Remove NaNs
chicago_all_vars = pd.concat([chicago_2010[["COMMUNITY AREA NAME", "CENSUS TRACT", 
                                        "BUILDING TYPE", "BUILDING_SUBTYPE"]], chicago_quant_vars], axis=1).dropna(subset=["TOTAL KWH"])
In [26]:
# Create a new dataframe that is grouped by census tract, where each feature from above 
# is totaled for the census tract, but this total is split amongst each building type we consider.
# For each census tract, match the median houshold income from the second dataset as an additional feature

for i in range(len(census_tracts)): 
    current_tract_df = chicago_all_vars[ chicago_all_vars["CENSUS TRACT"] == census_tracts[i]]
    dict_tract = {}
    for feature in range(len(features)):
        
        single_family = current_tract_df[current_tract_df["BUILDING_SUBTYPE"]  == 'Single Family'][ features[feature] ].sum()
        res_7plus = current_tract_df[(current_tract_df["BUILDING TYPE"]  == "Residential") &
                        (current_tract_df["BUILDING_SUBTYPE"]  == "Multi 7+")][ features[feature] ].sum()
        res_7less = current_tract_df[(current_tract_df["BUILDING TYPE"]  == "Residential") &
                        (current_tract_df["BUILDING_SUBTYPE"]  == "Multi < 7")][ features[feature] ].sum()
        comm_7plus = current_tract_df[(current_tract_df["BUILDING TYPE"]  == "Commercial") &
                        (current_tract_df["BUILDING_SUBTYPE"]  == "Commercial")][ features[feature] ].sum()
        comm_7less = current_tract_df[(current_tract_df["BUILDING TYPE"]  == "Commercial") &
                        (current_tract_df["BUILDING_SUBTYPE"]  == "Multi < 7")][ features[feature] ].sum()
        industrial = current_tract_df[(current_tract_df["BUILDING TYPE"]  == "Industrial")][ features[feature] ].sum()
        municipal = current_tract_df[(current_tract_df["BUILDING_SUBTYPE"]  == "Municipal")][ features[feature] ].sum()
        dict_tract.update(
        {features[feature]+" "+"SINGLE FAMILY": single_family,
         features[feature]+" "+building_types[0]: res_7plus,
         features[feature]+" "+building_types[1]: res_7less,
         features[feature]+" "+building_types[2]: comm_7plus,
         features[feature]+" "+building_types[3]: comm_7less,
         features[feature]+" "+"INDUSTRIAL": industrial,
         features[feature]+" "+"MUNICIPAL": municipal
        })
    dict_tract.update({
        "TOTAL KWH": [current_tract_df['TOTAL KWH'].sum()],
        "KWH/M^2 INTENSITY": [ (current_tract_df['TOTAL KWH'].sum())/ (current_tract_df["KWH TOTAL SQFT"].sum()) ], 
        "MEDIAN INCOME": [income_2013[income_2013["Census Tract"] == census_tracts[i]]["$ Median Household Income"].astype(float).sum()]
    })
    to_cat = pd.DataFrame(data = dict_tract)
    if i > 0: 
        chicago_vars_by_type = pd.concat([chicago_vars_by_type, to_cat]).reset_index(drop=True)
    else: 
        chicago_vars_by_type = to_cat

# Do one more sweep, through the predictor space now, and remove any tracts who are missing more than 
# one variable but who also (upon previous inspection) have uncharacteristically high consumption totals
discard_array = []

for i in range(len(X_all_vars)):
    zero_counter = 0
    for indx in range(1,len(X_all_vars.columns)):
        if X_all_vars.iloc[i, indx] == 0.0:
            zero_counter += 1
    if zero_counter > len(X_all_vars.columns)*0.5:
        discard_array = np.append(discard_array, 1)
    else:
        discard_array = np.append(discard_array, 0)

def plot_strength(X, y, y_pred, regression_name, set_type, model):
    x = np.linspace(0,20, 1000)

    y_2_0 = 2 * x
    y_0_5 = (.5) * x

    y_1_5 = (1.5) * x
    y_0_6 =  (.6667) * x
    plt.plot(x, x, color='green', linestyle='-.', alpha=.7)
    plt.plot(x, y_2_0, color='red', linestyle='-.',alpha=.7)
    plt.plot(x, y_0_5, color='red', linestyle='-.',alpha=.7)

    plt.plot(x, y_1_5, color='orange', linestyle='-.',alpha=.7)
    plt.plot(x, y_0_6, color='orange', linestyle='-.',alpha=.7)

    plt.scatter(y, y_pred)
    plt.xlabel(set_type+" y-values")
    plt.ylabel("Predicted "+set_type+" y-values")
    plt.title(regression_name)
    plt.xlim(0,20)
    plt.ylim(0,20)
    plt.text(15, .5, "R^2 = %0.3f "%(model.score(X, y)))

    plt.show()

This function above sets up a square-shaped scatterplot, with the observations on the x-axis and the predictions on the y-axis. If the fit is perfect, all points will lie on the green line, which has a slope of 1. If the fit is moderate, most of the points should lie between the green and orange boundaries, and if the fit is weaker, the points mostly lie between the orange and red boundaries.

From looking at both median household income distributions and the distribution of energy use intensity, it becomes clear the significance of the heavy right-hand skew, and how perhaps this dataset captures too much variance for a model to be able to quite accurately predict on a city-wide scale beyond a certain bias-variance threshold.

Thus, my focus should not be so much as to get the strongest model with the highest training $R^2$, but to seek out several models and tune them such that the testing $R^2$ increases without too much of a decrease in training strength. Before I even start modeling I brace myself for the fact that because I cannot split kWh contributions amongst building types and build separate building models which may very well work the best (due to data scarcity here), I will not be generating particularly resilient models because of the long yet flat skew of the energy use intensity curve. Instead, I can focus on tuning bias-variance and ultimately dicovering something about feature importance as I have set up my parameters with the maximum precision allowed by this dataset.

To get a glimpse at potential feature importance, I analyzed the highest energy use intensity and its corresponding parameter values, and found that there is no clear pattern shown amongst all building parameters, but median income is at its maximum, suggesting that it might play a significant role in subsequent modeling approaches.

# train on values within a given month, predict on test set values that are also within the same month
months = ['KWH JANUARY 2010', 'KWH FEBRUARY 2010',
       'KWH MARCH 2010', 'KWH APRIL 2010', 'KWH MAY 2010', 'KWH JUNE 2010',
       'KWH JULY 2010', 'KWH AUGUST 2010', 'KWH SEPTEMBER 2010',
       'KWH OCTOBER 2010', 'KWH NOVEMBER 2010', 'KWH DECEMBER 2010']
r_2scores = []
for i in months:
    m = melt[melt[i] == 1]
    x = m.drop(columns = ['CENSUS BLOCK','BUILDING_SUBTYPE', 'KWH MEAN 2010',  'TOTAL KWH', 'value', 'Month'])
    y = m['value']

    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2, interaction_only=True)
    x = poly.fit_transform(x)

    # test train split
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.2, random_state = 21)

    lr = LinearRegression(normalize = True)
    lr.fit(X_train, y_train)
    pred = lr.predict(X_test)
    r_2scores.append(lr.score(X_test, y_test))

0. Overview of Modeling Strategy¶

As mentioned at the end of the EDA section, my approach acknowledges the stark weaknesses in robust citywide energy data availability, so instead of perceiving success as obtaining the highest $R^2$, my intention in exploring three modeling approaches is to use them to guide bias-variance tuning in the basically untrimmed energy intensity range, by comparing training $R^2$ with testing $R^2$, which also indirectly tunes mean squared error.

1. Linear Regression - Is a Linear Feature Space Best?¶

I choose a degree 3 expansion here because between 2 and 3, 3 gives the highest scores overall, and any higher degree takes much too long computationaly to consider.

In [70]:
plot_strength(X_train, y_train, y_pred_train, "OLS with Polynomial Expansion", "Training", lr)

At a first glance, it seems like we have very little strength in the ordinary linear model, perhaps because there are some nonlinear parameter-response relationships at play. We do not have the worst bias-variance trade-off here, as we will see when the next modeling technique used really contrasts with what we have now.

When we perform a polynomial expansion on the feature space, our training accuracy shoots up to 1, suggesting that we are adjusting the model to become much more flexible and capturing the nonlinear features, but as a consequence we observe ridiculously low training and cross-validated $R^2$ scores, suggesting that we have made the model much too flexible now.

Since the ultimate goal for me is not to make the most resilient rather than the most biased model, I want to find a modeling technique that is in between both extremes, so I move next to shrinkage methods to see if I can tune a parameter penalty in hopes of improving my model.

Ultimately, some nonlinear fit would be preferred, but polynomial expansion on an ordinary least-squares regression proves to boost the flexibility too quickly.

Across training performance, Ridge squashes the score down by a factor of ten, but we see a notable improvement in testing and cross-validation scores, suggesting that we have improved the resilience of the model overall. Using Ridge alpha tuning via model cross-validation, training, testing, and cross-validated $R^2$ scores all increased, maintaining a healthy bias-variance balance while increasing the predictive strength of the model. This excercise further elucidates the importance of model cross-validation because it helps us understand how we can improve our model, what role the penalty factor alpha is playing in highlighting feature importance.

From the graoh of log-transformed coefficients, we observe that the Ridge coefficients were squashed down to almost zero as part of the penalty for including many parameters, but also becuase Ridge is trying to limit the flexibility of the model to hopefully boost its strength.

Because we normalized our features beforehand, we could infer something about feature importance by looking at which coefficients are highest, but because we used the polynomial transformation which does not preserve parameter names, we cannot yet deduce which parameters are most important in predicting energy end-use intensity for a given census tract.

To remedy this, we turn to regression trees next. We do not need to normalize, nor do we need to account for nonlinearity via polynomial expansion here.

For computational efficiency, I cannot use hyperparameter tuning via model cross-validation on all of my parameters of interest at once, so the parameters I specify below are based on stratified model cross-validation, although I recognize that the best parameter values may change with different combinations of hyperparameters.

Ultimately, I kept the learning rate as the default value, while the cross-validation demonstrated that the least absolute deviation loss function, less sensitive to outliers, would give me a more resilient model overall. Additionally, cross-validation indicated that I should only be using 75% of my feature space in my initial split in order to be able to explore various split patterns, instead of always leading with the same initial split that may be restricting me from other model-strengthening pathways.

Because there is a significant association between the two, and we commonly use income as an indicator of welfare, we can conclude that consumption intensity can aid in completing our picture of how "well-off" an area is.

5. Exploration of Howard et al.¶

In "Spatial distribution of urban building energy consumption by end use", a study is performed to use regression methods to predict energy consumption on a census block area using just a square footage parameter diffused into each building type. Effectively, the objective was to determine a coefficient of energy usage intensity ($kWh/m^2$). So, while fitting a spatial regression in order to make some conclusions about a city, I was motivated to recreate this analysis for Chicago, and to cross-reference our results with existing data from our robust Chicago Energy dataset.

In [92]:
# REPEAT SOME OF OUR DATA CLEANING BUT NOW JUST ON SQUARE FOOTAGE

# Create a new dataframe that is grouped by census tract, where each sqaure footage 
# is totaled for the census tract, but this total is split amongst each building type we consider.

for i in range(len(census_tracts)): 
    current_tract_df = chicago_all_vars[ chicago_all_vars["CENSUS TRACT"] == census_tracts[i]]
    dict_tract = {}

    single_family = current_tract_df[current_tract_df["BUILDING_SUBTYPE"]  == 'Single Family'][ "KWH TOTAL SQFT" ].sum()
    res_7plus = current_tract_df[(current_tract_df["BUILDING TYPE"]  == "Residential") &
                        (current_tract_df["BUILDING_SUBTYPE"]  == "Multi 7+")]["KWH TOTAL SQFT"].sum()
    res_7less = current_tract_df[(current_tract_df["BUILDING TYPE"]  == "Residential") &
                        (current_tract_df["BUILDING_SUBTYPE"]  == "Multi < 7")][ "KWH TOTAL SQFT" ].sum()
    comm_7plus = current_tract_df[(current_tract_df["BUILDING TYPE"]  == "Commercial") &
                        (current_tract_df["BUILDING_SUBTYPE"]  == "Commercial")][ "KWH TOTAL SQFT" ].sum()
    comm_7less = current_tract_df[(current_tract_df["BUILDING TYPE"]  == "Commercial") &
                        (current_tract_df["BUILDING_SUBTYPE"]  == "Multi < 7")][ "KWH TOTAL SQFT" ].sum()
    industrial = current_tract_df[(current_tract_df["BUILDING TYPE"]  == "Industrial")][ "KWH TOTAL SQFT"].sum()
    municipal = current_tract_df[(current_tract_df["BUILDING_SUBTYPE"]  == "Municipal")][ "KWH TOTAL SQFT" ].sum()
    dict_tract.update(
    {"SQFT"+" "+"SINGLE FAMILY": single_family,
         "SQFT"+" "+building_types[0]: res_7plus,
         "SQFT"+" "+building_types[1]: res_7less,
         "SQFT"+" "+building_types[2]: comm_7plus,
         "SQFT"+" "+building_types[3]: comm_7less,
         "SQFT"+" "+"INDUSTRIAL": industrial,
         "SQFT"+" "+"MUNICIPAL": municipal,
         "TOTAL KWH": [current_tract_df['TOTAL KWH'].sum()],
         "TOTAL EUI": [current_tract_df['TOTAL KWH'].sum() / current_tract_df['KWH TOTAL SQFT'].sum()]
    })
    to_cat = pd.DataFrame(data = dict_tract)
    if i > 0: 
        chicago_sqft_by_type = pd.concat([chicago_sqft_by_type, to_cat]).reset_index(drop=True)
    else: 
        chicago_sqft_by_type = to_cat

Interpretation and Conclusions (20 points)¶

The core objective of our analysis was to predict energy consumption while modeling on a citywide scale. We achieved this my splitting our approach in two sections: one that considered the effects of time-changing quantities and forecasted across months and years, and one that looked across space and predicted on the census tract level to make an observation about the city it is within.

Looking at the spatial forecasting component of this analysis, the main takeaway is that for a city whose consumption distribution is highly non-symmetric, developing a robust model that has this "one-size-fits-all" character is difficult and sometimes futile. There is much variation that exists on this scale, so it is almost predetermined that models will either be overfit to their training set while failing to predict accurately on testing or validation sets, or will approach a constant model with just slight perturbations in their ability to match flexibility. As a result, we took a tour through some classical modeling approaches in order to highlight how performance improves once we incorporate nonlinear predictor-response relationships, and once we start tuning hyperparameters that indirectly control model error.

In the end, the Gradient Boosting Regression tree model gave us the best balance across training, testing, and validation ($R^2$: 0.05; 0.1; 0.12), and it allowed us to grab information about feature importance to the prediction method. We discovered that building age of large commercial spaces (at 9.3%), median household income (at 8%), and occupied units of several-family buildings (at 6.7%) guided the prediction th5e most, so with this it is possible to branch off into several decision-making processes along the lines of implementing energy efficient design. From the perspective of a city planning official or a policymaker, using a model to predict energy end use intensity can help identify vulnerable areas to energy loss via outdated building design, or to assess a given city's need for demand response measures or distributed generation resources.

In the spatial forecasting section, we also used K-Nearest-Neighbors to look at the subset of our consumption data without the extreme skew, and still found that model performance does not exceed that of our cross-validated performances with the original data that we assume more accurately represents the physical system. In addition, we incorporated an economic factor of median household income into our feature space because we wanted to see if this feature was important enough in this analysis to potentially consider energy intensity as another indicator of welfare in the way income is by establishing some visible relationship between the two. Because the income parameter shows up as a top five performer, our analysis suggests that we can consider energy use intensity in Chicago as another indicator of welfare. Lastly, we performed a dataset validation exercise by just predicting on square footage to get kWh consumption, and found that, with some data smoothing, we can extract a fairly accurate prediction of energy use intensity by taking the sum of our coefficient space.

There is a great deal that can be told from square footage alone in predicting electricity output. When it comes to predicting on the level of individual residential buildings we can predict electricity consumption fairly well on a yearly timescale. However for whatever reason in the data we're working with there is a great drop in trying predicting individual electric consumption on a monthly scale. This is something that begs to be looked into further before even attempt to build a future model on a monthly scale. As it stands now that our model can only accurately predict for yearly electricity consumption is limited in applicability. We are still dealing with a great deal of noise in our residential data and additional building information data, especially appliance information, would likely go a great way in covering for these gaps.

Given the strength of square footage as a predictor, we sought out to see how well we could estimate electrical consumption from non-square-footage predictors and found that most of the accuracy can be made up without square footage. While we certainly imagined that there would be solidly linear relationships that did not require much data transformation, the building characteristic data was not specific enough or electrical consumption is simply too noisy to estimate with the data we have. We had to use interaction variables since we were performing ordinary least squares regression and Lasso and it made a substantial boost in accuracy. When looking through the model coefficients for our OLS and Lasso models, we were surprised to see that there were a number of coefficients that Lasso had actually boosted. The boosted coefficients appear to be interaction variables which signals there are strong data pairs in our building types but that maybe we should be building separate models for the different subtypes instead of treating the subtypes as a binary dummy variable.

It would not necessarily be advised to apply any of these models to other cities as there are likely weather characteristics that are driving electricity consumption trends. But for a city planner or official looking to better understand future electricity consumption, there is more data that needs to be collected but they largely can rely on previous models fitted on their city's or region's data.
